04976nam a22007455i 9781400888122DE-B159720210927121507.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210927t20172018nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97814008881227 a10.1515/97814008881222doi  a(DE-B1597)501144  a(OCoLC)1012881270  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 4aHN768.Z9bR343 2018 7aPOL0420402bisacsh04a303.48/40917672231 aGambetta, Diego, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aEngineers of Jihad :bThe Curious Connection between Violent Extremism and Education /cSteffen Hertog, Diego Gambetta. 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2017] 4cÂ©2018  a1 online resource (208 p.) :b44 b/w illus., 16 tables  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface to the Paperback Edition -- tPreface -- tThe Education of Islamist Extremists -- tRelative Deprivation in the Islamic World -- tRelative Deprivation Probed -- tThe Ideology of Islamist Extremism Compared -- tThe Education of other Extremists -- tMind- Sets for Extremists -- tConclusions -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe violent actions of a few extremists can alter the course of history, yet there persists a yawning gap between the potential impact of these individuals and what we understand about them. In Engineers of Jihad, Diego Gambetta and Steffen Hertog uncover two unexpected facts, which they imaginatively leverage to narrow that gap: they find that a disproportionate share of Islamist radicals come from an engineering background, and that Islamist and right-wing extremism have more in common than either does with left-wing extremism, in which engineers are absent while social scientists and humanities students are prominent.Searching for an explanation, they tackle four general questions about extremism: Under which socioeconomic conditions do people join extremist groups? Does the profile of extremists reflect how they self-select into extremism or how groups recruit them? Does ideology matter in sorting who joins which group? Lastly, is there a mindset susceptible to certain types of extremism?Using rigorous methods and several new datasets, they explain the link between educational discipline and type of radicalism by looking at two key factors: the social mobility (or lack thereof) for engineers in the Muslim world, and a particular mindset seeking order and hierarchy that is found more frequently among engineers. Engineers' presence in some extremist groups and not others, the authors argue, is a proxy for individual traits that may account for the much larger question of selective recruitment to radical activism.Opening up markedly new perspectives on the motivations of political violence, Engineers of Jihad yields unexpected answers about the nature and emergence of extremism.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Sep 2021) 0aEngineering studentsxPolitical activityzIslamic countries. 0aExtremistsxEducationzIslamic countries. 0aRadicalismzIslamic countries. 0aTerrorismxReligious aspectsxIslam. 0aTerroristsxEducationzIslamic countries. 0aViolencexReligious aspectsxIslam. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Political Ideologies / Radicalism.2bisacsh1 aGambetta, Diego.1 aHertog, Steffen, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aHertog, Steffen.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton University Press Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311060659140uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781400888122zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781400888122423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781400888122/original  a978-3-11-060659-1  Princeton University Pr